commit_message:
Add task to allow creation of provided roles

Some tempest tests require that a specific role is available for use.
Add a new variable, `tempest_roles`, to allow users to provide a list of
roles to create.

The existing tasks that create the 'reseller_admin' and 'remote_image'
roles have been removed. The correctly named 'ResellerAdmin' role is
already created by the os_swift role and the 'remote_image' is no longer
required since the glance tests make use of an admin user.

Depends-On: I66b7c639494d98fdb3baa52fe56c670e32dea3ce
Change-Id: I7987c5a4dbf50e97322a5b348c3cbd817b2672d6

commit_message:
Start sequence at 1 for deploy steps playbook

We should start the sequence at 1 instead of 0, since all our puppet
manifests assume the first step is 1. Trying to run our puppet manifests
with a hieradata value of step=0 actually results in an error because no
classes are included.

Change-Id: I93dc8b4cefbd729ba7afa3a4d81b4ac95344cac2
Closes-Bug: #1717292

commit_message:
Blacklist test_boot_server_from_encrypted_volume_luks in ocata

This test have been added in tempest 16.1.0 which has been promoted
to ocata but TripleO does not configure legacy encryption key manager
properly and barbican is not availabe in overcloud.

Change-Id: If6a2ae137a8df5c903c679a88f8868fea790d614
Closes-Bug: #1733574

As much as I'd like to consider the project list closed for Queens, I think we should consider this addition as it lives in the packaging space and already delivers value for its consumers. I like the idea of small agnostic images, and I think it would be great to have an official set of LOCI images for the Queens release.

Also bonus points for demonstrating the power and flexibility of our project infrastructure in delivering that specific use case successfully.

Could you address Emilien's question ? My understanding is that your images are not as customized/instrumented as the ones Kolla is using -- so while they could serve as a base to build Kolla images, you would likely not be able to reuse them directly and keep them lightweight ?"}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2017-10-25 17:30:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Without changes to kolla-ansible we cannot use LOCI images directly in kolla-ansible. However, the only bits missing are a few kolla-ansible specific scripts. We have discussed this with kolla and there are three options as i see it.

Option 1: Make kolla-ansible image agnostic by moving the runtime scripts to kolla-ansible -- this was rejected on multiple occassions

Option 2: redo the internals of the kolla build process to build a base layer with all the scripts needed in one layer, then use that layer as a base for building loci images

Option 3: Add the scripts to the loci image *after* we have built them. Out of all the options, this seems to be the best one. It requires no changes to Kolla and can be implemented on top of existing loci images without changes to those images.

With option 3 we would produce kolla compatibility layers which would tweak and customize the images to be consumable by kolla without drasticly affectign thier size. For example, the loci/nova image would be used as a base and push out loci/nova-api loci/nova-conductor loci/nova-scheduler etc etc, all sharing the loci/nova base with an additional layer of ~1MB on top.

This is all not implemented in an automated fashion yet, but i have some rough scripts that do that is purposed in option 3.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-10-26 14:31:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The mission of LOCI is to provide tooling that can output OCI[0]
compliant images in a CI/CD friendly way. A major goal, which we have
achieved, is to be able to build OpenStack images in a completely
air-gapped environment. Currently, the LOCI gates work completely by
consuming OpenStack-Infra mirrors for packages, pypi, and DockerHub
images.

LOCI has always been close to the OpenStack ecosystem. We are one of the
first ones to use secrets in zuulv3 outside of Infra themselves. We also
have worked with other projects to produce images per commit to the
services[1][2]. We extended openstack-infra/bindep[3] to support a new
syntax that allowed us to further simplify the LOCI build process while
making auditing of packages easier[4].

Some of the major benefits of LOCI images include:
  * Standard tooling for building (currently using Docker build)
  * Fast build times, most services output an image under 2 minutes
  * Small size, the LOCI Keystone image is under 40MB on Debian
  * CI/CD friendly, LOCI builds services entirely seperate from each
    other, so you can build Keystone seperately from Neutron without
    losing any benefits listed above
  * python3 support (though not all OpenStack services support python3)

LOCI itself only provides the tooling to build the images. It has no
deployment engine, and never will. The consumers of LOCI include several
offical OpenStack projects, namely Cinder[5] and OpenStack-Helm[6].
Outside of this, there are at least two companies using LOCI images
internally. Additionally, individuals such as myself and Chris Hoge
(hogepodge) use these images in personal deployments.

We will be implementing two periodic jobs that will reconsume zuulv3
jobs from Kolla-Ansible and OpenStack-Helm when those gates are ready.
This will allow us to demonstrate the functionality of LOCI images in
two seperate OpenStack projects on a regular basis. We have discussed
this with both PTLs from both communities and both are happy to work
with this us to make this happen.

While LOCI has been around for a year, we will be making our debut 1.0.0
stable tag for the OpenStack Queens release.

We are working on moving our meeting to one of the #openstack-meeting
channels to be in compliance with the OpenStack Project Team guidelines
as mentioned here[7][8].

To address the "4 opens":
  * Open Source: check! All code is license compatible
  * Open Commnuity:
      - We have not held any elections yet, but given acceptance by the
        TC we would do so at the next available cycle.
      - We are not, as a group, affiliated with any individual company.
        In fact, the majority of the work done in LOCI was on personal
        time for the contirbutors
  * Open Development:
      - We have been using the OpenStack eco system extensively
      - We are cooperating with existing projects as shown by the points
        in previous paragraphs as well as the links below
  * Open Design:
      - We have, in an unofficial capacity, done most of our design work
        at the PTGs or Summits. We would love to do this in an official
        capaciity!
      - We primarily use IRC for collaboration, but I do monitor the
        mailing list. I suspect as time moves forward, and development
        slows, the mailing list will get used more, as has been the case
        with other projects.

commit_message:
LOCI - OCI images for OpenStack

The mission of LOCI is to provide tooling that can output OCI[0]
compliant images in a CI/CD friendly way. A major goal, which we have
achieved, is to be able to build OpenStack images in a completely
air-gapped environment. Currently, the LOCI gates work completely by
consuming OpenStack-Infra mirrors for packages, pypi, and DockerHub
images.

LOCI has always been close to the OpenStack ecosystem. We are one of the
first ones to use secrets in zuulv3 outside of Infra themselves. We also
have worked with other projects to produce images per commit to the
services[1][2]. We extended openstack-infra/bindep[3] to support a new
syntax that allowed us to further simplify the LOCI build process while
making auditing of packages easier[4].

Some of the major benefits of LOCI images include:
  * Standard tooling for building (currently using Docker build)
  * Fast build times, most services output an image under 2 minutes
  * Small size, the LOCI Keystone image is under 40MB on Debian
  * CI/CD friendly, LOCI builds services entirely seperate from each
    other, so you can build Keystone seperately from Neutron without
    losing any benefits listed above
  * python3 support (though not all OpenStack services support python3)

LOCI itself only provides the tooling to build the images. It has no
deployment engine, and never will. The consumers of LOCI include several
offical OpenStack projects, namely Cinder[5] and OpenStack-Helm[6].
Outside of this, there are at least two companies using LOCI images
internally. Additionally, individuals such as myself and Chris Hoge
(hogepodge) use these images in personal deployments.

We will be implementing two periodic jobs that will reconsume zuulv3
jobs from Kolla-Ansible and OpenStack-Helm when those gates are ready.
This will allow us to demonstrate the functionality of LOCI images in
two seperate OpenStack projects on a regular basis. We have discussed
this with both PTLs from both communities and both are happy to work
with this us to make this happen.

While LOCI has been around for a year, we will be making our debut 1.0.0
stable tag for the OpenStack Queens release.

We are working on moving our meeting to one of the #openstack-meeting
channels to be in compliance with the OpenStack Project Team guidelines
as mentioned here[7][8].

To address the "4 opens":
  * Open Source: check! All code is license compatible
  * Open Commnuity:
      - We have not held any elections yet, but given acceptance by the
        TC we would do so at the next available cycle.
      - We are not, as a group, affiliated with any individual company.
        In fact, the majority of the work done in LOCI was on personal
        time for the contirbutors
  * Open Development:
      - We have been using the OpenStack eco system extensively
      - We are cooperating with existing projects as shown by the points
        in previous paragraphs as well as the links below
  * Open Design:
      - We have, in an unofficial capacity, done most of our design work
        at the PTGs or Summits. We would love to do this in an official
        capaciity!
      - We primarily use IRC for collaboration, but I do monitor the
        mailing list. I suspect as time moves forward, and development
        slows, the mailing list will get used more, as has been the case
        with other projects.

[0] https://www.opencontainers.org/
[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/512398/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/512793/
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/506502/
[4] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/512063/3/bindep.txt
[5] https://github.com/openstack/cinder/tree/master/contrib/block-box
[6] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/472961/
[7] https://docs.openstack.org/project-team-guide/open-community.html#public-meetings-on-irc
[8] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/512471/

Change-Id: I4152237a2fbde5f827aae4524f87e7bf2798e956

+1 for the idea.

If you look at the cleanup_host() function we can see many project-specific conditionals copying logs/artifacts to the "devstack/logs" directory that will then be shown in gate. So, I think it makes sense to have that hook which projects could, in their own tree, take care of selecting the artifacts that makes sense to be exposed in tree for their jobs run.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2017-11-22 13:35:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

post-run playbooks are run unconditionally after the job and are a great place to collect things. The long-term vision for devstack-gate is to retire it in favor of the devstack base job for devstack jobs and the multinode base job for multi-node jobs that don't actually need devstack itself.

I don't see any problems with this patch, but I wanted to nudge towards making use of zuul v3 native features instead if possible."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2017-11-22 13:39:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Thanks for the pointer Monty!

We've already migrated the playbooks to the networking-ovn tree (project which we are trying to collect the logs) and I think we can do it in the post-run then."}, {'account_id': 23804, 'date': '2017-11-24 10:45:03.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

function. This patch adds a generic way for projects to collect logs,

commit_message:
Add a new hook ``collect_artifacts_hook``

Right now, there's a lot of project specific code in the cleanup_host
function. This patch adds a generic way for projects to collect logs,
configuration files, etc. regardless of the job exit code.

This hook will be called unconditionally as the last step before
cleanup.

Change-Id: I2fd2afd06b73cab68e427c94e4d2064fe727702f
Signed-off-by: Daniel Alvarez <dalvarez@redhat.com>

'}, {'created': '2017-10-31 18:25:53.000000000', 'message': 'Add supports-accessible-upgrade tag to ironic*

This adds the "supports-accessible-upgrade" tag to ironic and
ironic-inspector. They both meet the criteria for this tag:

https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/tags/assert_supports-accessible-upgrade.html#requirements

During an ironic upgrade, the bare metal nodes that end users access
are unaffected. this is tested in gate, via the grenade jobs. For
example, in the 'ironic-grenade-dsvm' job, nova is used to get a bare
metal instance from old ironic. After old ironic is shut down and
before new ironic is started up, grenade runs the resource phase:
'verify_noapi pre-upgrade'. Although ironic's verify_noapi() is a
noop [1], nova comes to the rescue with it's verify_noapi() [2]
where it pings its bare metal instance (which it got from ironic).

ironic-inspector only deals with bare metal nodes prior to them being
available to end users, so it doesn't touch any resource that is
accessible to the end user.

commit_message:
Add supports-accessible-upgrade tag to ironic*

This adds the "supports-accessible-upgrade" tag to ironic and
ironic-inspector. They both meet the criteria for this tag:

https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/tags/assert_supports-accessible-upgrade.html#requirements

During an ironic upgrade, the bare metal nodes that end users access
are unaffected. this is tested in gate, via the grenade jobs. For
example, in the 'ironic-grenade-dsvm' job, nova is used to get a bare
metal instance from old ironic. After old ironic is shut down and
before new ironic is started up, grenade runs the resource phase:
'verify_noapi pre-upgrade'. Although ironic's verify_noapi() is a
noop [1], nova comes to the rescue with it's verify_noapi() [2]
where it pings its bare metal instance (which it got from ironic).

ironic-inspector only deals with bare metal nodes prior to them being
available to end users, so it doesn't touch any resource that is
accessible to the end user.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/7f924cf30f546ae76eb149ae86201073ded396b2/devstack/upgrade/resources.sh#L123

[2] https://github.com/openstack-dev/grenade/blob/dbee4eed16cc0b2a2143f18936d6c85fd3940da0/projects/60_nova/resources.sh#L136

Change-Id: I20941939e9f2331c6a0983e3c14c988cae936bd2

commit_message:
Install python-apt before hooks run

Previously this charm had relied on python-apt being installed by
the principle. As charms migrate to py3 this is no longer a safe
assumption and actually never was. This change ensures that
python-apt is installed before immediatly. This follows the same
pattern as other charms by adding an install and install.real
files.

Change-Id: I9fe2a031df736b867d4f277448a4d8649fa8de64

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-18 11:48:45.000000000', 'message': "Fix WSGI application

* Partial revert of 0a82af18abbf070a058cb757af68926f9b66798f
  to restore main() method
* Add global `application` variable which will be set by main method to
  problem to preserve the fix from 0a82af18abbf070a058cb757af68926f9b66798f.
* Add check for application name starting with '_mod_wsgi' to ensure
  application runs in Devstack as well (Devstack does not use the entry point)

commit_message:
Fix WSGI application

* Partial revert of 0a82af18abbf070a058cb757af68926f9b66798f
  to restore main() method
* Add global `application` variable which will be set by main method to
  problem to preserve the fix from 0a82af18abbf070a058cb757af68926f9b66798f.
* Add check for application name starting with '_mod_wsgi' to ensure
  application runs in Devstack as well (Devstack does not use the entry point)
* Modify Devstack plugin to run WSGI entry point rather than app/wsgi.py from
  module directory.

Change-Id: I07001dccb663ed4e6e3347089ab96e6f8ec196d4
Depends-On: I9e4bbd6fd48454e37985ed5c408e8b935d535304
Story: 2001197

commit_message:
Depth argument is prome to failure for ansible<2.3

I sometimes get this error under ansible 2.1/2.2 during the
clone of each role:

``An exception occurred during task execution.
To see the full traceback, use -vvv.
The error was: AttributeError: 'AnsibleModule' object has no attribute
'warn'

failed: [localhost] (item=
{'name': u'apt_package_pinning',
 'scm': u'git', 'src': u'https://git.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-
    ansible-apt_package_pinning',
 'version': u'origin/stable/ocata'
}) =>{
"failed": true, "item": {
  "name": "apt_package_pinning", "scm": "git",
  "src": "https://git.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-ansible-
  apt_package_pinning", "version": "origin/stable/ocata"
 },
"module_stderr":
 "Traceback (most recent call last):
  File \"/tmp/ansible_Ukqz_Z/ansible_module_git.py\", line 1038,
  in <module> main()
  File \"/tmp/ansible_Ukqz_Z/ansible_module_git.py\", line 952, in main
  clone(git_path, module, repo, dest, remote, depth, version, bare,
   reference, refspec, verify_commit)
  File \"/tmp/ansible_Ukqz_Z/ansible_module_git.py\", line 391, in clone
  module.warn(\"Ignoring depth argument. \"
  AttributeError: 'AnsibleModule' object has no attribute 'warn'",
"module_stdout": "", "msg": "MODULE FAILURE"
}

An exception occurred during task execution. To see the full traceback,
use -vvv. The error was: AttributeError: 'AnsibleModule' object has no
attribute 'warn'
``

When commenting the depth argument, the issue is skipped.

Change-Id: I1deb22f536bcec24e0d4e3c6d49ed12010dd1f31
(cherry picked from commit 596b1b2af176a09a6636e7ffd3a8f7030fbc3eed)

commit_message:
Add ceph paths to usr.bin.nova-compute aa profile

The current profile does not include ceph paths
which breaks nova-compute if
libvirt-image-backend=rbd when in enforce mode.
Also fix access to /tmp and /var/tmp.

Change-Id: Ie03a43ef73ca5f97f4f9e5edcefd261a0e36abf9
Closes-Bug: 1732492

commit_message:
Do not use “-y” for package install

According to "code conventions" [1], do not use "-y" option.
Instead, use apt-get install package, yum install package,
or zypper install package.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/doc-contrib-guide/writing-style/
code-conventions.html

Change-Id: Id5120af11c4f7a4d3d24b10ca2fdf3a243d482f4

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-23 22:20:11.000000000', 'message': 'Make sure step conditional is first in the conditional list.

During ugprade-non-controller we iterate over the task using step
variable.  By prepending the step check we skip the other checks if we
are not in the right step.

Hence we can have variable in conditional that are defined in only one
step as this won’t get evaluated because of the lazy evaluation used
by ansible.

An example:

 - task: register something
   shell: "ls -lrth /etc/are_you_there"
   register: is_it_there
   tags: step3
 - task: use variable
   shell: “rm /etc/are_you_there”
   when: is_it_there.rc == 0
   tags: step3

This is converted to:

 - task: register something
   shell: "ls -lrth /etc/are_you_there"
   register: is_it_there
   tags: step3
   when: step|int == 3
 - task: use variable
   shell: “rm /etc/are_you_there”
   when:
    - is_it_there.rc == 0
    - step|int == 3
   tags: step3

Now if step == 2, this fails as is_it_there.rc is undefined but “use
variable” task uses it first.

By prepending we have:

   - step|int == 3
   - is_it_there.rc == 0

is_it_there.rc will not be evaluated when step != 3.

Change-Id: I061b7e40578321e6281c0f5e783d733b25f5ffef
Closes-Bug: #1734214
Partial-Bug: #1733924

commit_message:
Make sure step conditional is first in the conditional list.

During ugprade-non-controller we iterate over the task using step
variable.  By prepending the step check we skip the other checks if we
are not in the right step.

Hence we can have variable in conditional that are defined in only one
step as this won’t get evaluated because of the lazy evaluation used
by ansible.

An example:

 - task: register something
   shell: "ls -lrth /etc/are_you_there"
   register: is_it_there
   tags: step3
 - task: use variable
   shell: “rm /etc/are_you_there”
   when: is_it_there.rc == 0
   tags: step3

This is converted to:

 - task: register something
   shell: "ls -lrth /etc/are_you_there"
   register: is_it_there
   tags: step3
   when: step|int == 3
 - task: use variable
   shell: “rm /etc/are_you_there”
   when:
    - is_it_there.rc == 0
    - step|int == 3
   tags: step3

Now if step == 2, this fails as is_it_there.rc is undefined but “use
variable” task uses it first.

By prepending we have:

   - step|int == 3
   - is_it_there.rc == 0

is_it_there.rc will not be evaluated when step != 3.

Change-Id: I061b7e40578321e6281c0f5e783d733b25f5ffef
Closes-Bug: #1734214
Partial-Bug: #1733924

commit_message:
Disable tempest jobs for doc only changes

For doc only changes, there is no need to run tempest jobs which
require more time. This commit disables the tempest jobs if
doc only changes,
only unit-test changes

Closes-Bug:#1732829
Change-Id: Idc0604beff383f435705acfd55de57258a71332c

commit_message:
Standardise log field naming

Use the same field name for extracting all log messages to make it
simpler to parse the output from fluentd.

Closes-Bug: #1723459

Change-Id: I55b86061c8f70b25cf88e394fdfc78fa3c85c79f

commit_message:
Remove setting of version/release from releasenotes

Release notes are version independent, so remove version/release
values. We've found that projects now require the service package
to be installed in order to build release notes, and this is entirely
due to the current convention of pulling in the version information.

Release notes should not need installation in order to build, so this
unnecessary version setting needs to be removed.

This is needed for new release notes publishing, see
I56909152975f731a9d2c21b2825b972195e48ee8 and the discussion starting
at
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-November/124480.html
.

Change-Id: I594c14139dd8a3b313e95898ff86508fc7a40878

commit_message:
Fix postgresql jobs and cleanup zuul job files

This commit removes the services/projects not required by tests.
Earlier, ceilometer(gnocchi backend) doesnt seem to support postgresql,
hence jobs are failing. As ceilometer is currently removed now from the
supported drivers, removing the same here.

Change-Id: Iafb92de6ca2bf502264c77da73d6ab9871a48bbb

> Oops - I misunderstood the intent here. This appears to be some
 > sort of infrastructure verification/health check rather than what I
 > thought it was (a host connectivity verification).

Yes, this is a general healthcheck before doing more in-depth healthchecks of connectivity. Here it tests the connectivity from nodes to the infra, and that all the infra services are in a good state.

I am planning to write another playbook to use what's in openstack_user_config, loop through the net, and do ping checks between what seems logical to me. commit_message:
Add infra healthchecks

This adds a playbook, oriented for users, to automatically test
their installation after the setup infrastructure test.

These are connectivity tests to the infrastructure, and ensure
that containers would behave properly when running the openstack
playbooks.

These are based on the general assumption that ppl would use
a container management network.

Change-Id: Idb331dd6a72439c838708216500039f628b2760c

commit_message:
Constraint ansible installation

Rally installs ansible, in an unconstrained way.

To pass linters, we skip the lint job on the test
shell command.

Change-Id: Ic830cf81b3cc691aafb7a97819e0ce68e48dd809

commit_message:
Initial Zuul v3 role jobs

This patch implements an initial set of jobs intended to match
the current job execution method. It does not intend to improve
how the jobs are executed - only to replicate what is currently
in openstack-infra/openstack-zuul-jobs and provide the platform
to iterate on.

On top of that I am trying to uniformize what's in the
usual tests folder. This may fix what's happening in gates not
happening on my machine.

Change-Id: I78c32b740fc291b7373ffa0c19015946decaf743

commit_message:
Do not implement reload for novnc/spice service

The nova-novncproxy and nova-spicehtml5proxy services do not
support using a HUP signal to reload, so the init file for
them should not implement a reload.

Depends-On: Id4b9caa1cdfd0f53023548c4ede5d497d64c873d

commit_message:
Do not implement reload for novnc/spice service

The nova-novncproxy and nova-spicehtml5proxy services do
not support using a HUP signal to reload, so they need to
be restarted instead.

This patch ensures that these services are restarted, and
also fixes a bug that hasn't been noticed before where if
the Placement API and other nova services are implemented
on the same host/container then the other services would
not be restarted. It would play out like this:

- The first task asks to reload all nova services execute
  against all nova hosts, except those running the placement
  api. This results in only the compute hosts getting the
  reload.

- The second task only asks the nova placement API to
  restart. This leaves out all the other nova services
  which are on the same host.

Change-Id: Id4b9caa1cdfd0f53023548c4ede5d497d64c873d
Needed-By: I36e2200e2ca43d87208d2c4edb17b98654bb121e

commit_message:
Fix writing text after py3 conversion

During the recent py3 conversion of the charm a couple of places
where the charm writes text in binary mode were missed. This
fixes that problem. Without this fix the charm errors with:

"TypeError: a bytes-like object is required, not 'str'"

Change-Id: I5c2af1dce12092c1ba1be4b4ad9a50261000e886

commit_message:
Passing 'default_boot_option' to Ironic jenkins jobs

The default value of Ironic configuration variable
"[deploy]/default_boot_option" is being changed to "local".
Few of the Ironic jenkins job were relying on the default value of
this option to "netboot". Explicitly changing the
"[deploy]/default_boot_option" to "netboot" for these impacted
jobs.

Change-Id: I1692037759690dad2c096c35876d3656103f0f70
Partial-Bug: #1619339

Job is fixed and green, let's make it voting so that we can't break it again :)"}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2017-07-14 13:46:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2017-07-14 14:01:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I would really love to see this job voting as soon as possible. Unfortunately, this is not easy as we think.

Some facts why I'm against doing it *today*:

* All upgrade jobs (and not only this one) are non voting on master.
* None of upgrade jobs are part of TripleO Promotion pipeline so if something merges in OpenStack that would break upgrades, we wouldn't catch it during Promotion jobs and our gate would be broken afterward. It doesn't happen every day but we have seen in the past it could happen and cause damage, specially at this time of the cycle.

What I suggest is to get some feedback from folks who work on the Promotion pipeline and see the progress made to have container jobs running in RDO Software Factory.

In any case, I think we should wait to have the job in a promotion pipeline (in TripleO CI or RDO) before making it voting, so we avoid CI downtime."}, {'account_id': 8042, 'date': '2017-07-14 14:05:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

This job has been very stable lately, the only breakages occuring as a
consequence of ignoring its results when merging patches. Let's make
the job voting and keep it green.

commit_message:
Tripleo: Enable periodic jobs to run in check-tripleo pipeline

Tripleo periodic jobs run also promotion, and sometimes they need manual
triggering.
At the moment the manual triggering is activated with a hack in the
job_type, but it misses important parameters like the job timeout.
This change adds alias jobs of periodic jobs on check pipeline for
tripleo-ci project only, and only if a file with a specific name is
added to the change

Change-Id: I7cb318345e91bd0a11371556180b7f8075f40819

commit_message:
zuul: run TripleO jobs with new zuulv3 layout

Configure the layout to execute the scenario001 jobs.
Note that baremetal job will be run on stable/pike and container on
Queens and beyond.

A note has been added in comment explaining more details.

Change-Id: Ibbe35a84a4de14f02d4db0d9d5c7a9b5d01ec8d0
(cherry picked from commit f2cb62b72e9fb7e10b74826d019de31afc443b85)

commit_message:
zuul: run TripleO jobs with new zuulv3 layout

Configure the layout to execute the scenario001 jobs.
Note that baremetal job will be run on stable/pike and container on
Queens and beyond.

A note has been added in comment explaining more details.

Change-Id: Ibbe35a84a4de14f02d4db0d9d5c7a9b5d01ec8d0
(cherry picked from commit f2cb62b72e9fb7e10b74826d019de31afc443b85)

commit_message:
[WIP] Implement Keystone zero-downtime upgrade

IT SHOULD BE MERGED INTO ORIGINAL PS AFTER STRATEGY IS OK

  1- Expand and migrate database in first keystone node
  2- Upgrade all nodes sequentially along with updation of each node's
     configuration file with latest release version
  3- Last keystone node, contract database
  4- Task has var not_run_all: True is never run on all host at same time

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/keystone/upgrading.html#upgrading-without-downtime

Co-Authored-By: Surya Prakash Singh <surya.singh@nectechnologies.in>
Co-Authored-By: Eduardo Gonzalez <dabarren@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Duong Ha-Quang <duonghq@vn.fujitsu.com>

Change-Id: I5726384b9f19c2837cd8e7d0621ec81b500bb6d6
Partially-Implements: blueprint ks-rolling-upgrade-role

commit_message:
ovsfw: Use multiple priorities in RULES_*_TABLE

The OpenFlow spec says packets shouldn't match against multiple flows
at the same priority or the result is undefined. In ovsfw, 8 priority
levels are needed to comply with this rule.

Note: unlike overlapping TCP port ranges cases, the current version
of OVS seems to handle this case magically.

Change-Id: I6deaee8dbe81453285b1fc685282952bc9456949
Closes-bug: #1708092

commit_message:
Increase interface detach polling period

We increase max interval to cover all waiting time from retries in
Nova detach.
With Nova's current design (with virt driver) it will do retry at
time(in seconds): 2, 6, 12, 20, 30, 42, 56
And with new time interval (set max waiting time to 12s) in Heat:
0.5, 1.5, 3.5, 7.5, 15.5, 27.5, 39.5, 51.5, 63.5
So we can cover and check till nova actually stop retry.
Related-Bug: #1585858

Change-Id: I912ab9ab8b1b13b13cec479a1b7d8b2c083c2d09

Increase the transaction timeout to 30 seconds for functional tests

Off late we are seeing lot of transaction timeouts in the functional tests.
So increasing the timeout to 30 seconds.

commit_message:
Check that os_net_config_need_upgrade is defined

For the os-net-config steps, the os_net_config_need_upgrade
and os_net_config_has_config output variables are checked,
however these are both registered in a shell step that
includes ignore_errors.  If an error occurred in the shell
step these variables will be undefined, causing the playbook
to fail (observing it on compute node upgrade).

Change-Id: I08fdd72ab0bb245a9725f0da5dae428465a582d7

commit_message:
Fix wrong data in jsonfile generated by osrf writer

The redundant commit of backend leds to the addition of wrong data that
usage is None and period is repeated.
{"usage": {}, "period": {"begin": "xxxx", "end": "xxxx"}
Closes-bug: #1516968

Change-Id: Ifee499bc645f30d0ffcc53c2e2c9d05587e76940

commit_message:
Add neutron-vpnaas docs pub job to zuul layout

One of the requirements[1] for Neutron stadium projects is to have
in-tree developer documentation.  This creates a stub for that.  We can
expand on it once the stub is in, but this will permit us to set up
publishing while we iterate on it.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/neutron/stadium/governance.html#checklist

Change-Id: Id5650a6b4cebb65d964610cde3d4685d242007d7

commit_message:
Add dynamic table for our tested Scenarios

This change adds in a dynamic table to our documentation so that we're
able to generate a table of all available scenarios and mark where
services are tested within. To make the dynamic scenario generation
easier the AIO scenario conf setup has been moved into it's own variable
file.

The file doc/source/contributor/scenario-table-gen.html has been touched
allowing sphinx to import and generate the required table as needed.

Change-Id: Ief5d180491d3a330890d6bfa06d43f565dd26103
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Fix the bug of create a resource when use long name

When use tacker create a resource like 'vnffgd-create, vnffg-create,
vnfd-create' .etc. with long name, the server will response a
"internal server error". So we set the NAME_MAX_LEN for resource
name in the "RESOURCE_ATTRIBUTE_MAP".

Change-Id: I3217dec158fdaba415e712f4e4a10468ad2f8ab5
closes-Bug: #1734010

commit_message:
Fix the error of create VNF with very big name

Create VNF with very big name, instead of giving proper message.
It is giving the internal server error. But the server should
return the length of name exceeds maximum length of 255.

Closes-Bug: #1716358

Change-Id: Id490e5389741625331f0ab6abc18f502cb8071aa

commit_message:
Fix could not load modules when devstack installing

These modules have no config OPTS, so we remove them:
tacker.tacker.policy_actions.log.log,
tacker.tacker.policy_actions.respawn.respawn,
tacker.tacker.policy_actions.autoscaling.autoscaling

Change-Id: I553449ad1ef4e0182531ecb0c19938630a977bd1
Closes-Bug: #1734031

commit_message:
Fix devstack for gnocchi collector

The gnocchi collector can't work when cloudkitty is deployed by devstack.
Because the gnocchi repository has been changed.

Change-Id: Id035524b77f32ed971f3d51f3c79f9b44241f7a1
Closes-bug: #1733734

commit_message:
Fix 'List' command filters do not accept unicode symbols

When using the name or description to filter the share list,
share group list, share network list or snapshot list, if the
name or description is unicode symbols, the query will fail due to the
invalid str value. This change is to fix them.

Change-Id: I73ed2b675542d3aeedc9efdba08067819bf7d3e4
Closes-bug: #1712988

commit_message:
Switch from ostestr to stestr

This change updates the tox.ini file to call stestr
directly instead of going through ostestr.
For more background you can read the ML posting:
    https://goo.gl/TFvcxy
So now you won't need `--n` to run single tests, and you
can also supply regex directly without even the `--`.
For example:
  `tox -epy27 $regex`

Change-Id: I2b9b7fbd60b2cc5eea8af01e20cde5714df5027a

commit_message:
Comment out the option oslo_messaging_rabbit.rabbit_password

The option oslo_messaging_rabblt.rabbit_password has been
deprecated. Therefore the option is commented out in the
sample config files etc/trove/ directory.

Change-Id: I613087217c88b8a5dbf8dfc3f51e48b8fe4c84c8

* Work with HostState class as well.
* Move all fake class to fakes module.

commit_message:
use agent api def from neutron-lib

The agent extension's API definition was moved into neutron-lib with
commit Iae4746aa2e3f68a7120696a12a6ae717115dbc31
This patch consumes it by removing the rehomed code and using the
APIExtensionDescriptor for the parent class of the extension.

NeutronLibImpact

Change-Id: I18aebec1e2b5b361d9b96192d4a59e5424c6a80b

commit_message:
Let cluster action_*** load the right schema.

apischema.py defind some schema to validate the request. Current code
under cluster schema has some item like "create","add_shard",
"grow" etc. Call "create" method pass the action "create", but
call method like "add_shard" atcually pass the action "action".
https://github.com/openstack/trove/blob/master/trove/common/api.py#L157
And this will lead to method get_schema will return "{}".
https://github.com/openstack/trove/blob/master/trove/cluster/service.py#L54
And then lead to method vallidate_request actually do nothing.
https://github.com/openstack/trove/blob/master/trove/common/wsgi.py#L402

Change-Id: I5dc9a6639445ce37c8b2213717cf17c3a64d1716

commit_message:
Update bindep.txt for doc builds

https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/project-testing-interface.html#documentation
specifies that doc dependencies need the doc tag in bindep, use it.

Leave test environment in for transition period until we use the new
scripts.

'}, {'created': '2017-11-23 16:12:00.000000000', 'message': 'Add bindep for testing

Change-Id: Iadccf82775b311ace8f09e203c38a8946a1e5843
'}, {'created': '2017-11-23 19:22:37.000000000', 'message': "Add bindep + Remove setting of version/release from releasenotes

Some packages were removed from the fallback bindep, add our own.

Release notes are version independent, so remove version/release
values. We've found that projects now require the service package
to be installed in order to build release notes, and this is entirely
due to the current convention of pulling in the version information.

Release notes should not need installation in order to build, so this
unnecessary version setting needs to be removed.

Unset  html_static_path to fix building.

This is needed for new release notes publishing, see
I56909152975f731a9d2c21b2825b972195e48ee8 and the discussion starting
at
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-November/124480.html
.

commit_message:
Add bindep + Remove setting of version/release from releasenotes

Some packages were removed from the fallback bindep, add our own.

Release notes are version independent, so remove version/release
values. We've found that projects now require the service package
to be installed in order to build release notes, and this is entirely
due to the current convention of pulling in the version information.

Release notes should not need installation in order to build, so this
unnecessary version setting needs to be removed.

Unset  html_static_path to fix building.

This is needed for new release notes publishing, see
I56909152975f731a9d2c21b2825b972195e48ee8 and the discussion starting
at
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-November/124480.html

Co-Authored-By: Andreas Jaeger <aj@suse.com>
Change-Id: Iadccf82775b311ace8f09e203c38a8946a1e5843

commit_message:
Backport zuulv3 configuration to stable branches

This change contains the following changes squashed:

Add copy project-config's legacy-requirements-cross-* jobs

These are going to be rewritten to native zuulv3 jobs
in the next commit.

Needed-By: I3b0dbdcc02a0a8cff0c52701fadf7632648afb97
Change-Id: I3b9a86528350242c4d785d0f49c318de6c29ec75
Closes-Bug: #1730673

Add requirements-check job

This is a straight copy of the original gate-{name}-requirements job,
except it copies the script over to the host rather than depending on a
baked-in copy of the script. Followups should rework it to stop using
zuul-cloner.

(jlk) updated to fix pep8 errors so that the patch can land.

Change-Id: I734db3b3e4d445e15084d1ca6e60cf2fe392385d

Fix check-requirements

Fix check-requirements: The assumptions with remote branch are not valid
anymore with Zuul v3, the change is on the proposed branch, check against
HEAD^1 instead.

Use the command module instead of script to get stdout in the
job-output.txt.gz file. Zuul v3 currently will not record the output from script
module in that file, only when command is used.

Note that the script module copied the file to the remote system - the
system where the tests are run - while command does not do this. But
the command is already on the remote system, use correct path for it.

Co-Authored-By: James E. Blair <corvus@inaugust.com>
Change-Id: Ib44332b4daf63b9d3fca6eadf0b4825614ca4aeb

Add a Zuul v3 native cross-check job

Convert the existing legacy-cross-* jobs over to the
new cross-check-job.

Adds a small bump to upper-constraints in order to test
the success of this review.

Co-Authored-By: Dirk Mueller <dirk@dmllr.de>
Change-Id: Iba6a025e3a10185ad1d8217244b967713cace3f6

Change-Id: I6018ec17cc435a54fa9aed83bf53a27967e78831

commit_message:
Update filters to support over-commit

The default filters that we have do not properly support setting an
over-commit ratio. This change makes it possible for us to set the
over-commit ratios as expected and instance scheduling is NUMA aware.

Change-Id: I33ae92e73b699d34d9382c65a74dc78ccab53ea3
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 6a783fe5d882bcfeb36adf86412be55a4bbb175e)

[{'created': '2017-11-23 15:24:24.000000000', 'message': 'Extend openstack_command

This patch extends openstack_command to accept an array in addition to a
string as an argument.

This allows the use of openstack_command in cases where an argument
contains protected spaces.

Examples:

mistral execution-create my_workflow \
    '{"names": ["John", "Mistral", "Ivan", "Crystal"]}'

barbican secret list --name chef_test_secret --format value -c"Secret href"

Without this patch, all arguments have to be passed as a single string
which openstack_command splits on white space regardless of any
quotation marks. Therefore, the examples above will fail.

Change-Id: I0419a1526beb103839a3cf235eba6c41d9d946d5
Closes-Bug: #1723949
(cherry picked from commit d232f34b4c0b8b2a2b4272c06421d4af1eb08ed1)
'}]
commit_message:
Extend openstack_command

This patch extends openstack_command to accept an array in addition to a
string as an argument.

This allows the use of openstack_command in cases where an argument
contains protected spaces.

Examples:

mistral execution-create my_workflow \
    '{"names": ["John", "Mistral", "Ivan", "Crystal"]}'

barbican secret list --name chef_test_secret --format value -c"Secret href"

Without this patch, all arguments have to be passed as a single string
which openstack_command splits on white space regardless of any
quotation marks. Therefore, the examples above will fail.

Change-Id: I0419a1526beb103839a3cf235eba6c41d9d946d5
Closes-Bug: #1723949
(cherry picked from commit d232f34b4c0b8b2a2b4272c06421d4af1eb08ed1)

commit_message:
Remove setting of version/release from releasenotes

Release notes are version independent, so remove version/release
values. We've found that projects now require the service package
to be installed in order to build release notes, and this is entirely
due to the current convention of pulling in the version information.

Release notes should not need installation in order to build, so this
unnecessary version setting needs to be removed.

This is needed for new release notes publishing, see
I56909152975f731a9d2c21b2825b972195e48ee8 and the discussion starting
at
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-November/124480.html
.

Change-Id: I4151b338d3e038bda3f97e862ac3a3d9eddecbe6

commit_message:
Change deprecated auth_plugin to auth_type

In the keystone_authtoken section, the key has already been changed
from auth_plugin to auth_type. This patch does the same for the trustee
section (see [1]).

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/heat/pike/install/install-ubuntu.html

Change-Id: Idd82170107043bc2497261c34859844343e783a1
(cherry picked from commit fb1c143c651d5328a138f85bd6fe5aff95a18a55)

commit_message:
Grant admin role in heat domain to heat_domain_admin

This patch grants heat_domain_admin the admin role in the heat domain
(rather then in the service project).

We use :grant_domain instead of :grant_role, because we are setting a
role in a domain, not in a project.

Note that for the user to actually exist in the heat domain, a
sufficiently recent openstackclient cookbook is required -- otherwise
the domain_name attribute is ignored during user creation.

Also, we remove the user_name attribute (gets ignored by resource
action).

Change-Id: I747e2dedbc517cc3deb2675590fb982459c560a0
(cherry picked from commit dc2d594b0535b524486c13ed52128d8efff6d334)

commit_message:
Remove uw_nginx jobs

Nginx with uWSGI has been the default keystone deployment since Pike.
The uw_nginx jobs should be no different than the functional jobs at
this point, but they have been incorrectly using the uw_apache tox
environment anyway.

Change-Id: I73c01b9899819da96f51744d5fba12a05bb7ec2c
(cherry picked from commit ada86843ee6744d5e21a76050afd7f96d79671a1)

Change auth config to keystone v3

under the "keystone_authtoken" and "service_credentials" groups.

commit_message:
Remove multinode legacy gate

This patch set removes the legacy multinode gates as those are
being transitioned to zuul v3, and the legacy multinode gates have high
rate of failure.  The single nodes will remain a while longer as a sanity
check until the new gates are fully functional.

Change-Id: Ie8f685eb2737c91d37c670db24d877e7efbfe0f2
